Unknown Russula here, ok, this was found last week, and I kept thinking the species would come to me here. I haven’t been able to get a clear spore print of it, must be too young. The gills are kinda yellow, but don’t know if it is a yellow spore print. The cap is dry, smooth, not visid. The pileus peels free for some way from the edge, lets say half way to the center. And the taste is mild, mostly very mild, but maybe very slightly slowly peppery, but I would put it in the mild camp. One thing the flesh when cut and bruised turns slightly yellow, just cut it doesn’t stain and stays white.

So, I don’t know on this one.

description: No idea here, psathyrella? Paneolus? Little skinny brown jobs…

Ok, I think this is a psathyrella, but not sure. Might be stropharia. But it is a fairly good size attractive mushroom. And I find non-cespitose groupings of these of 20-30 mushrooms at a time in the ground. But usually near woody debris.

Nice dark purple-brown spore print.

After discussion with people at the Santa Cruz Fungus Fed. fair setup (Jan 13-14, 2007), I now have these as Stropharia riparia.

These were kinda neat, a tight group of these coming out of a crack in a stump, growing from deep down in the crack. The group was like two dozen of these at together. I tried to get them out by the base, but couldn’t get down into the crack, so most broke off in the step somewhere. I did get a group of a few that were growing together, so it might have been one big cespitose cluster. Nice fuzzy bases two.

The parts that broke off oozed a nice red blood where broken.

[Admin – Removed ’Unknown – ’ from name in preparation for the support for Name objects.]

Just a single big one, in the middle of a grassy lawn.

The small volval cup wouldn’t come up out of the grass, so this is what I got.
Hard to notice these, they are just dirty brown lumps in the dirty brown ground. Almost think they are just lumps of clay, or stones, until you cut them open.
Finding these here and there as just little tufts of small mushrooms. Only a inch or two high, all grouped together on the edges of grassy lawns.
Just little brown jobs, lots of them in around bits of woody debris, just about everywhere now.

Saw lots of these, and thought they were alnicola. They really look like it, and they can be about the same, although alnicola has more zoning on the cap, and less scrobiculation on ave.

But the one clear difference is the milk in the gills, these have a yellow staining milk, and yellow stained gills. So they are scrobiculatus.

In the last two photos it is easy to see the yellow stained gills. But the last photos is supposed to show the yellow stained milk, I cut two parallel lines in the gills there. You can almost see the line of yellow milk if you look close.
More of these, seeing then around a lot lately. In among the duff of oak leaves. Usually they are pretty small and dried out, different looking from up in the woods in the hills.

Ok, this year, it is like the sixth sense here, I see comatus — all the time…

Really this year, it is silly, I mean each time I go wondering around through grassy areas and looking in the landscaping at the edges of lawns and parks, I see these.

I was away for a week, and I came back to find easily 6-8 large groupings of 12-20 mushrooms all going bad, and turning black. And a week later it was about the same.

Don’t know if this is just a good year for these, or if I am just seeing more for some reason.

Cleaning up some other observations here.

These are nice buttons of this bolete, I found a few under this live oak. The pores are red, but no spores yet. The button nice and fat, and stains blue anywhere, esp. when cut.

I am calling these amygdalinus. Although I can’t seem to tell the difference between this and erythropus, except for vague statements about brownish and pinking cap colors. So, I will go with amygdalinus until someone can show me what is the clear difference between these.

More of the brown capped one in the swampy area. Let it go for two days on the spore print this week, and got a slight brown one, maybe.

Still have no idea what this is…
place_guess: Los Trancos Preserve, Palo Alto, California, USA

description:
Some unknown Lepiota here, and a really small one. But I think full grown. Not sure I found a discription of one this small, but also with no scales or veil on the stipe. The stipe is awfully clean on these.

Just to add some numbers, the caps are 1.8-2 cm, and stipe is 2.5 cm long and 3-4 mm wide.

Ok, after being unknown for a few weeks, finally have an answer on this one. I was able to confer with Dr. Else Vellinga of Berkeley, at the SF group/Oakland Museum fungus fair this last weekend (12/3/2006). And she took away the dried material and photos, and got back to me.

This is L. neophana, and the ref. for the species is Sundburg, W.J., Mycotaxon 34: 239-248, and can be found here:

http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/cyberliber/index.htm

And the specific ref. for this species is:

http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/...

Which looks pretty good, and was found before in San Mateo Co.

Else said she is going to keep this material for the herbarium in Berkeley.

She also mentioned that L. neophana was first sited from the midwest, but after looking at more meterial it is probably true that the easter neophana is a different species than the western one found here. Esp. since the eastern species is supposed to be a lighter color, and not break up into scales like this one.

Good, one more unknown down… lots more to go…

description:
Some notes were sent into me by Dr. Else C. Vellinga:
-—————————————-
Your picture of Lepiota seminuda in fact is a species in the L. sequioarum complex. Cystolepiota seminuda is small (caps up to half an inch, more or less), with a rounded cap and a fine granulose covering, which in young fruitbodies hangs down the cap margin in triangular teeth. The stipe is thin, also finely powdery, with a wine-red tinge to it under the cover. A ring is not really present, there may be traces left on the stipe where the cap broke off from the stipe Your specimen here is bigger, with a flatter cap, radially fibrillose silky, with a prominent ring on the stipe (and lots of microscopic characters which also distinguish it from C. seminuda). Unfortunately, what has been called L. sequoiarum here is in fact a complex of 5 or 6 different species. I’m in the midst of figuring it all out.
-——————————————
So, thanks to Else, and what do you know?

description:
Ok these are Armillaria mellea as far as I can tell. But I looked at:

http://botit.botany.wisc.edu/toms_fungi/armkey.html

And I don’t really understand the details. It seems that mellea is a east coast only one? But I’m not sure what will be a west coast caespitose Armillaria that is not on conifers…

In any case, I am going with mellea, it has all the features.

One difference with the “sinapina” I found in the hills this weekend, was that the “sinapina” has a creamy light yellow spore print, and this mellea has a white-white, as white as the bright white paper I use, spore print.

The photos here are like a time-lapse series of the same cluster over 4 days.

And here is a little guy found out there, probably too small and young to tell, but I thought I would throw it out there are see. Maybe I shouldn’t bother with these single little guys, but if anyone has an idea…

description:
Ok, not sure if there are two different species here. The bottom photo is what I recognize as quercophilus, with the little brown spot on the cap, and the dark hair like stipe.

The first photos, in the field and at home, seem to be very similar. But the caps are more white, and the stipe is slightly thicker, half whitish clear, with only the base dark.

But I don’t know, maybe the whiter cap and clear stipe is just a younger developing version of the mushroom.

10/24/2007 – After discussion with Dr. Desjardin about these this year, it turns out the white small ones, are not young M. quercophilus, but Hemimycena sp., and probably undescribed from CA, since no one has done work on this genus here, yet. Looking at the photos here, it looks like I have two mixed up, and I need to separate the photos to two different observations.

I thought it was L. seminuda from the discription in Arora, but now it is L. sequioarum, from comments by Else Vellinga. See observation 1081.

This is a young subtomentosus, where the pores haven’t opened up enough yet, and obviously is more yellow when young. But looking at other photos of mine, not as yellow as the flaviporus.

The funny thing is that this was a single mushroom found, but it was attached to a rock under the ground, and it was really attached to that rock. So, it is not a tuber, but just a rock.

If this isn’t a honey mushroom and there is a better idea, please pass it along.

Ok, looking the info from the comment, it does look more like “sinapina”. The veil remanents on the cap, and the single growth seem to point to this species.

description:
I’ve been looking in this area in the past, and haven’t found this one before, but I usually don’t get out until after Thanksgiving. But sure enough, get out a little earlier and there they are. Found a few up there this time, and these were the best, others getting old, so mid Nov. is getting late.

I was up there three weeks ago and found nothing, no fungus of any kind, but now they are getting old. So, there is a narrow window of finding these.

Ok, I know most call these calyptrata, but I thought I would put these down as lanei to keep the controversy of the species name going here.

description:
I previously submitted this as a Cardinal MH. Author and authority Kathy Biggs disagreed, noting the blackish legs and suggesting it was a Red-veined. I attempted to respond via an edit but got into a mess with lined-out IDs and incorrect ID withdrawn messages, so Im reposting it with a more detailed comment and support, viz: 

This is a Cardinal, the blackish-looking legs notwithstanding. For one thing, Red-veineds around here have a short flight season. Theyre abundant at all our higher-elevation ponds from early June til late July and then they disappear; by Nov 1, the date of this shot, theyre long gone. This one is lit up from behind making the venation look all red, but those are the stubbier, broader wings and the lighter pterostigmae of a Cardinal.

PS: Dear Ms Biggs: Thank you for your book.* A little story: My parents were active birders for 60 years; when they couldnt get out any more I would send them what we called odopix. They enjoyed using your book to identify my shots -- they called it their odobook and it lived next to their iMac. 

* 2nd ed. 2000, signed with a silver pen! Dont remember where I got it...
